Narrative: A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), operating in autonomous mode, was gradually slowing to a stop for a red traffic signal on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] in San Francisco when it was rear-ended by a passenger car (Vehicle 2) traveling directly behind. The Zoox vehicle operator then disengaged from autonomy. Both vehicles proceeded a few feet further and pulled over to exchange information. Both the Zoox vehicle and Vehicle 2 sustained minor damage. The police were not called. The Zoox vehicle operator reported back pain after the collision.

At 2:23pm:  WeRide driverless vehicle (vehicle 1) with a safety operator seated in front passenger seat, was travelling 45mph without much traffic ahead when a BMW x3 (vehicle 2) travelling in the adjacent left lane and in the same direction, merged into vehicle 1's left front quarter panel. Vehicle 1 and Vehicle 2 sustained moderate damages.
After discussing the incident with vehicle 2's driver, they admitted they were attempting to make an upcoming right turn off the expressway. They initiated 2 consecutive right lane changes abruptly before hitting vehicle 1 on their last attempted lane change.
After the initial impact, vehicle 1 was forced out of the initial lane, onto a divide, and ultimately came to a stop on the shoulder of the expressway. At this time both occupants of vehicle 1 and vehicle 2 were able to assess respective damages and exchange information. It was determined that there were no injuries. WeRide Vehicle (Vehicle 1) required a tow back to the facility.

While nearly through the intersection, the cyclist abruptly veered left into the path of the Zoox vehicle and accelerated toward the front of the Zoox vehicle in violation of a red crosswalk signal and in violation of the Zoox vehicle's right-of-way. The Zoox vehicle appropriately braked hard in response to the cyclist's maneuver, but contact was unavoidable. The eBike laterally impacted the Zoox vehicle's right front fender and body side, then the cyclist impacted the right front body of the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle then came to a full stop. The cyclist then rode over to the sidewalk and remained briefly stopped on the sidewalk before getting back on the eBike and riding away. The Zoox vehicle cleared the intersection, then pulled over on [XXX], and shortly after was towed from the scene for inspection. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage to the right front body. The police were not called. No injuries were reported nor apparent with the cyclist.
The content of this report is unchanged from the initial report and provides complete information to date for this incident.

An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomy was stopped at a red light in the right travel lane on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX] and [XXX] in San Francisco. The Zoox vehicle cleared the intersection, then pulled over on [XXX], and shortly after was towed from the scene for inspection. The Zoox vehicle sustained minor damage to the right front body. The police were not called. No injuries were reported nor apparent with the cyclist.

While traveling northbound on[XXX] in Martinez, a car pulled out of a driveway on the right side without right of way and collided with the right side of May's vehicle (t-bone.)
May's vehicle was traveling at approximately 20 MPH in a residential neighborhood, and was approximately 1m left of lane center when a black vehicle exited a driveway on the right from behind a fence, facing the road and May's vehicle. This vehicle did not slow down or stop until entering into the roadway and collided with the May vehicle's right side. AVO attempts to swerve to the left but is unable to avoid a collision. 
The primary factor that led to the collision was the other vehicles action proceeding without the right-of-way into the side of the May vehicle. Upon further inspection, it was determined that we did not predict this collision until it was too late to avoid it even by veering. The velocity of the other vehicle was underestimated and was largely given only yield policies as having the most significant likelihood. There is some room for improvement in our response, which we plan to implement in future software releases, namely, an emergency veer policy must exist that is capable of moving quickly and far enough to possibly avoid the collision, more accurate reporting of velocity for slow-moving agents, estimate acceleration when assessing risk, improvements to predictions of the probability of an agent yielding, and adjusting our risk assessment so that it is heading dependent and more risk would be associated with passing close in front of another vehicle.

On January [XXX], 2025 at 6:07 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, CA was in a collision involving a passenger vehicle near the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX].

Shortly after, a passenger vehicle came to a stop behind the Waymo AV. While the Waymo AV and the other passenger vehicle were stopped, an SUV approached from behind at an extreme rate of speed and made contact with the passenger vehicle behind the Waymo AV, which then made contact with the rear bumper of the Waymo AV. According to the San Francisco Police Department, the Waymo AV then began to rotate clockwise and, as it was rotating, the front of the SUV made contact with the passenger side of the Waymo AV. The rear of the Waymo AV then made contact with the rear driver side corner of another passenger car that had just begun to proceed straight on northbound [XXX]. According to the San Francisco Police Department, at least two other vehicles were involved in the crash and one of the occupants of the vehicles involved in the crash and a domestic animal were declared deceased at the scene. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV, the passenger vehicle behind the Waymo AV, and the SUV sustained severe damage. The extent of the damage to the other three vehicles is currently unknown. Waymo received notice that five passengers in four of the vehicles involved sustained injuries of varying severity. 
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because of a fatality. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On December [XXX], 2024 at 8:28 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in Los Angeles, CA was in a collision involving two SUV's, a passenger car, and a pick up truck on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was stopped in autonomous mode facing south at a red light as the lead vehicle in the second from the right lane when an SUV traveling northbound in an oncoming traffic lane ran the red light.  As the oncoming SUV entered the intersection, it made contact with a passenger car traveling east on [XXX].  The oncoming SUV continued through the intersection and swerved to narrowly miss a pedestrian before making contact with the front of the Waymo AV and the front driver side of a stationary pickup truck to the right of the Waymo AV.  The impact from the oncoming SUV caused the Waymo AV to contact another SUV that was also stationary to the left of the Wayo AV at the red traffic light.  The Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode immediately before the oncoming SUV made contact.  At the time of the impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode.  The Waymo AV sustained damage to the front and rear of the vehicle, necessitating a tow from the scene.  The oncoming SUV sustained damage to the front and driver side.  The stationary SUV that was contacted sustained damage to the passenger side.  The Waymo test driver was transported to a local hospital for medical treatment.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request no. 1 of Standing General order 2021-01 because an individual involved was transported from the scene to a hospital for medical treatment, a vehicle involved was towed away, and because of airbag deployment.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This is a duplicate of NHTSA Report ID: 30270-9476-2.

On November [XXX] at 1:27pm, Car 1 (weride av) - while ADS Engaged -  was making a legal, protected, left turn from [XXX]. Car 1, turning onto [XXX], performed the turn from the second lane from the left and was travelling 11 mph when Car 1 then slowed down while still in the intersection. It is at this time Car 1's safety driver disengaged ADS of Car 1 this put car 1 into manual mode. It is at this time when car 2 (Ford f-150 XLT), traveling at 18 mph, approximately less than 13 feet away from Car 1 and also making a left turn from [XXX] within the same lane as car 1, struck and rear ended car 1 while both cars were still in the intersection.
At the time of impact Car 1 (Weride AV) ADS was not engaged.
Car 1 sustained minor damage to its rear bumper and car 2 sustained minor damage to front bumper. Both parties pulled over to exchange information.
Car 2 did not provide Registration and Insurance for their respective car. Car 2's driver did give us driver's license information but the driver of the vehicle (car 2) at the time of the incident was a different person than that represented on the driver's license presented.
There was no injuries, no property damage and no police were called.

A Zoox vehicle (Vehicle 1), was completing a mission traveling southwest on [XXX] in San Francisco. On July [xxx], 2024, at 12:59 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in [XXX], California was involved in an alleged collision with a non-motorist (cyclist) at a parking garage exit on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX].

The Waymo AV remained stationary as the cyclist passed in front of the vehicle, slowed, and appeared to begin to dismount. The cyclist then reached out a hand and made contact with the front passenger side of the stationary Waymo AV, backed the bicycle up slightly, dropped the bicycle, then fell to the ground. 
At the time of the possible impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present. The cyclist received medical attention at the scene and was reportedly transported to a hospital by local emergency services. The Waymo AV did not sustain any damage. 
Even though this event may involve intentional contact by the bicyclist with a stationary Waymo AV and the occurrence of actual impact between the Waymo AV and the cycle is not clear, Waymo is reporting this event as a crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a media report included an allegation of a crash and because a vulnerable road user (cyclist) influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved and reportedly was transported to a hospital for medical treatment as a result of the event. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On July [XXX], 2024, at 12:59 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in [XXX], California was involved in an alleged collision with a non-motorist (cyclist) at a parking garage exit on [XXX] between [XXX] and [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was exiting a parking garage onto [XXX], between [XXX] and [XXX]. As the Waymo AV approached the garage exit, it stopped for a cyclist who was approaching from the left. The Waymo AV remained stationary as the cyclist passed in front of the vehicle, slowed, and appeared to begin to dismount. The cyclist then reached out a hand and made contact with the front passenger side of the stationary Waymo AV, backed the bicycle up slightly, dropped the bicycle, then fell to the ground. 
At the time of the possible impact, the Waymo AV's Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present. The cyclist received medical attention at the scene and was reportedly transported to a hospital by local emergency services. The Waymo AV did not sustain any damage. 
Even though this event may involve intentional contact by the bicyclist with a stationary Waymo AV and the occurrence of actual impact between the Waymo AV and the cycle is not clear, Waymo is reporting this event as a crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a media report included an allegation of a crash and because a vulnerable road user (cyclist) influenced the driving task of a vehicle involved and reportedly was transported to a hospital for medical treatment as a result of the event. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On February [XXX], 2024 at 2:34 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a bicyclist on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX] and came to a stop at a 4-way stop sign intersection at [XXX]. When it was the Waymo AVs turn at the intersection, the Waymo AV entered the intersection to proceed straight. At this point, a delivery truck traveling eastbound on [XXX] was already in the middle of the intersection (the delivery truck arrived at its stop sign first and proceeded into the intersection before the Waymo AV). As the Waymo AV passed the rear of the delivery truck, an occluded bicyclist who was traveling behind the delivery truck became visible and was making a sharp left turn onto northbound [XXX], in front of the Waymo AVs path. The cyclist had entered the 4-way stop intersection without stopping or yielding. The Waymo AV detected the bicyclist, applied heavy braking, but was unable to avoid contact with the bicyclist before coming to a full stop. 
At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode. The Waymo AV sustained minor body damage, and the bicyclist reported minor injuries and damage to their bicycle. The Waymo AV remained stopped in the intersection for approximately one minute, and after the path was clear, resumed driving for a short period of time. The Waymo AV was then returned to the scene by one of Waymos roadside assistance specialists. The Waymo AV did not require towing and was returned to the depot in manual mode.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vulnerable road user was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

A Ghost ADS-equipped car was driving engaged Northbound on [XXX]. As always, there were two safety drivers in the car. Traffic was moving in all four lanes at or near the speed limit. The Ghost vehicle was in the right-middle lane. Another vehicle (the "lead" car) entered into the Ghost car's lane from the right. While there were numerous vehicles ahead of the Ghost car before that vehicle entered the lane, the lead vehicle blocked the view of the lane before it. Throughout the incident, traffic in the other three lanes continued at a steady pace.
When the lead vehicle entered into the lane ahead of the Ghost car, the Ghost car applied the brakes to accommodate the intrusion and then continued to match the speed of the lead car. The lead car suddenly slammed the brakes. The Ghost car followed suit, reducing its speed from 19 mps (42.5 mph) to 4.7 mps (10.5 mph) within the next three seconds. The Ghost car was able to match the rapid speed reduction of the lead car and avoid contact.
The driver following the Ghost car was not able to respond as quickly as the Ghost ADS. When the following driver began to apply the brakes, the car was about five meters behind and was traveling at 6.5 mps. At the point of impact, the Ghost vehicle was traveling at 4.78 mps (10.7 mph), matching the lead car. There were no injuries. The vehicles suffered only cosmetic damage, the drivers exchanged information, and the Ghost safety drivers returned to home base in conventional mode.

The passenger car behind the Waymo AV was rear-ended by a pickup truck, causing the front of the passenger car to make contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. Cruise is submitting this updated report to indicate in the Post-Crash Information section that it has received a California Highway Patrol Traffic Collision Report in connection with the reported incident.  There are no other changes to Cruise's previous submission (30412-6395-3): A Cruise autonomous vehicle (AV), operating in driverless autonomous mode, was at a complete stop in response to a red light on southbound [XXX] at the intersection with [XXX]. A dark colored Nissan Sentra was also stopped in the adjacent lane to the left of the AV. As the Nissan Sentra and the AV proceeded through the intersection after the light turned green, a pedestrian entered the crosswalk on the opposite side of [XXX] across from the vehicles and proceeded through the intersection against a red light. The pedestrian passed completely through the AVs lane of travel but stopped mid-crosswalk in front of the Nissan Sentra. Shortly thereafter, the Nissan Sentra made contact with the pedestrian, deflecting the pedestrian in front of the AV. The AV braked aggressively but, shortly thereafter, made contact with the pedestrian. The AV then attempted to pull over out of traffic, pulling the individual forward, rather than remaining stationary. The driver of the Nissan Sentra left the scene shortly after the collision. Police and Emergency Medical Services (EMS) were called to the scene and the pedestrian was transported by EMS. On November 2, 2023, Cruise submitted a voluntary recall report to NHTSA relating to the AVs response after the collision, based on updated analysis that Cruise performed since the filing of the previous submissions.

On June [XXX], 2023 at 3:39 PM PDT, an Apollo Autonomous Vehicle ("Apollo AV") operating in San Francisco, California, was in a collision involving a scooter on [XXX] near [XXX]. 
The Apollo AV was traveling westbound on [XXX] passing the intersection with [XXX]. The intersection has stop signs clearly installed at all four ways, which require vehicles to make full stop before entering the intersection. The Apollo AV made a full stop, entered and passed approximately 75% of the intersection. A person on scooter coming southbound from [XXX],  approached the intersection. The person on scooter entered the intersection without stopping, then made contact with the passenger rear-side of Apollo AV. Our Apollo AV operator immediately disengaged the AV, pulled over to the closest safe place to park, got out of the car to check the person on scooter, who already left the scene on his scooter without exchanging any information. The Apollo AV had small minor paint scratch, which do not need repair. The police were not called.

Narrative:
VIN # VG9A2CB2CIV[XXX] 
At approximately 5:54 p.m. on Wednesday, August [XXX], 2023, P84, travelling eastbound on [XXX], approached the three-way stop at [XXX] and [XXX]. P84 arrived at the intersection at the same time as two other vehicles: a grey van heading northbound on [XXX] and a red sedan heading westbound on [XXX]. The safety driver yielded to the northbound vehicle, which proceeded to make a right-hand turn eastbound onto [XXX]. After allowing the intersection to clear, the safety driver onboard P84 confirmed that it was safe for the shuttle to proceed through the intersection. As the shuttle entered the intersection, a second vehicle travelling northbound on [XXX], a white sedan, entered the intersection intending a left-hand turn onto westbound [XXX]. Both vehicles entered the intersection simultaneously, subsequently colliding at a low rate of speed in the middle of the intersection.  
At approximately 5:57 p.m., the Beep Command Center (BCC) was informed by the safety driver that P84 was involved in a minor collision with another vehicle at the intersection of [XXX] and [XXX]. The incident response protocol was initiated, and a supervisor dispatched to the scene. Local law enforcement (San Francisco Police Department) was contacted to report the collision but declined to respond given the minor nature of the collision, directing both parties to exchange information. After the Beep supervisor arrived on scene at approximately 6:49 p.m., the safety driver and supervisor removed the shuttle from the roadway and exchanged insurance information with the driver of the other vehicle. 
Damage to both vehicles was noted to be very minor. The shuttle sustained light scuffs, chips, and small paint transfer. The other vehicle sustained a small dent on the fender. Neither vehicle required towing, and both were safely driven from the scene. 
Beeps safety driver was subsequently subjected to a standard post-collision drug & alcohol screening which has since cleared.  
Contributing Factors 
Based on an analysis of the available evidence, Beep has determined the following factors may have contributed to the higher likelihood of a collision occurring in this instance: 
1.The white sedan failed to yield to P84 in accordance with California state law governing intersection priority.
2.The slight bend in P84s path to accommodate the lane shift through the intersection may have reduced the available stopping distance as the white sedan was not perceived as an obstacle in P84s path until it proceeded further into the intersection.
Incident Findings 
Beep developed the following findings regarding this incident:
1.P84 behaved as expected, detecting and maintaining awareness of the white sedan in the moments preceding the collision, commanding hard braking maneuver, and achieving a 3m/s2 deceleration rate once the white sedan encroached on P84s path.
2.The safety driver observed California state law and had the right of way when releasing P84 into the intersection.
3.The safety driver could have avoided the collision by using the emergency stop. The safety driver indicated that they were aware of the other vehicle through the duration of the incident and were aware of the proper procedure in this scenario but panicked in the moment.
Mitigation:
Implement a priority zone to account for the slight bend in the shuttles path and for future vehicles that may fail to yield.

A Ghost autonomous vehicle was hit by crash debris while traveling on [XXX].  The Ghost vehicle neither hit nor was hit by another vehicle.  The Ghost car was traveling in AV mode with two safety drivers.  Traffic slowed quickly, apparently due to a crash ahead of the Ghost car.  Consistent with their training, the Ghost driver took control of the car by manually braking and disengaging the autonomous system.  The car was traveling 55.3 mph when the driver began to brake.  The Ghost car stopped without impacting the preceding car.  A Mercedes car immediately following the Ghost car also came to a stop without impacting the Ghost car.  Ghost's understanding based on communications at the scene is that a Grand Cherokee traveling behind the Mercedes tried to swerve to avoid impacting the Mercedes but clipped the Mercedes and rolled over.  To Ghost's knowledge, nobody in the Grand Cherokee was injured.  The Ghost drivers heard a noise and then found that the rear bumper of the Ghost car had been damaged, which Ghost believes resulted from crash debris. The Ghost drivers drove the Ghost car back to the garage in conventional mode.

On July [XXX], 2023 at 1:13 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a passenger car on [XXX] at [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX] in autonomous mode when it began to brake as it approached a stopped van on the oncoming side of the narrow roadway. The Waymo AV test driver transitioned to manual mode and began proceeding straight when the passenger side front sensor housing of the Waymo AV made contact with the driver side mirror of a passenger car parked along the curb on southbound [XXX]. At the time of the impact, the Waymo's Level 4 ADS was not engaged and a test driver was operating the Waymo AV in manual mode. Both the Waymo AV and the passenger car sustained damage.
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this crash under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01. Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available. This is a duplicate of report 30270-6129-1.

The collision occurred while the Waymo AV was stopped in the leftmost lane of a two-lane, one-way road at the intersection of [XXX] at [XXX]. The Waymo AV was facing a green light, but stopped before entering the intersection because traffic was stacked on the other side of the intersection, leaving no space for the AV. The Waymo AV was traveling southbound on [XXX] and preparing to make a right turn onto westbound [XXX]. As the Waymo AV was yielding to cross-traffic and preparing to make a right turn, a cyclist was traveling eastbound on [XXX] and heading the wrong way in the bike lane. The cyclist then turned left, northbound, onto [XXX], continuing to travel the wrong direction in the bike lane. As the Waymo AV slowly proceeded forward, the cyclist passed the Waymo AV and made contact with the rear passenger side sensor of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the drivers seating position). The Waymo AV sustained damage and the cyclist did not stop, leaving the scene without exchanging information.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a cyclist was involved. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On June [XXX], 2023 at 11:18 PM PT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in Los Angeles, California was in a collision involving a pick-up truck on [XXX] at [XXX]. 
The Waymo AV was traveling eastbound on [XXX] and stopped at a stop sign at the intersection of [XXX] when a pick-up truck approached the Waymo AV from behind and made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV. At the time of the impact, the Waymo AVs Level 4 ADS was engaged in autonomous mode, and a test driver was present (in the drivers seating position).
The Waymo AV test driver then took manual control of the Waymo AV and the pick-up truck then made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV again. The Waymo AV test driver pulled towards the side of the road and stopped. TThe pick-up truck then made contact with the rear of the Waymo AV again and when the test driver of the Waymo AV resumed movement, the pick-up truck followed the Waymo AV and repeatedly made further contact with the Waymo AV. At one point the pick-up truck driver verbally harassed the Waymo AV test driver. The Waymo AV test driver was eventually able to elude the pickup truck and wait nearby for law enforcement to arrive. The Waymo AV sustained damage.
Waymo is reporting this crash under Request No. 1 of Standing General Order 2021-01 because a vehicle involved was towed away. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.

On May [XXX], 2023 at 3:27 PM PDT a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California was in a collision involving a cyclist on [XXX] near [XXX].
The Waymo AV was traveling westbound in the left lane on [XXX] and had just passed [XXX] when it detected an oncoming pickup truck traveling eastbound in the Waymo AVs lane. The Waymo AV stopped and the pickup truck re-entered the correct lane for eastbound traffic and passed the Waymo AV. The pickup truck was immediately followed by a large group of cyclists traveling eastbound in multiple lanes of the roadway, including the right lanes and on the wrong side of the double-yellow centerline. The Waymo AV sustained damage.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: The subject Mercedes-Benz vehicle was driving in stop and go traffic on the [XXX] in Gardena, California with the L3 ADS activated. The test route selected by the driver in the vehicle's navigation system indicated an upcoming exit, so the driver began to prepare for a lane change towards the highway exit by deactivating the L3 ADS and activating the turn signal. Once the vehicle was in conventional driving mode, the driver looked for a gap in the adjacent lane to merge towards the exit lane, applied the brakes, and slowed the vehicle down. The SUV following the Mercedes-Benz vehicle did not respond in time to the vehicle's braking and contacted the rear of the Mercedes-Benz approximately 10 seconds after the L3 ADS was deactivated.  The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were driven from the scene of the incident.

Operating Entity: Mercedes-Benz Research and Development North America
Narrative: Mercedes-Benz has conducted a review of the incident and the following is based on that review. The subject Mercedes-Benz Drive Pilot test vehicle was traveling between 15-20 mph in the #2 northbound lane on the [XXX] in California in stop and go traffic with the L3 ADS activated by the driver. The vehicle's ADS determined that a truck traveling in the adjacent lane had a trajectory towards the Drive Pilot's lane, and so the Mercedes-Benz test vehicle autonomously applied the brakes to avoid a collision. After applying the brakes and bringing itself to a standstill, the Mercedes-Benz was then struck in the rear bumper by a trailing semi-truck that did not stop in time. No injuries were reported, no airbags deployed in either vehicle, and both vehicles were able to be driven from the scene of the incident. The Mercedes-Benz vehicle experienced minor damage to the rear bumper, and no damage was observed on the semi-truck at the scene. The CA Traffic Collision Report for the subject incident noted a violation of California Vehicle Code 22350 (unsafe speed for traffic conditions) by the semi-truck in the #2 lane that struck the rear bumper of the Mercedes-Benz.

As reported by Argo AI to Ford on September [XXX], 2022 (Report # 30290-3913-1), an Argo AI Autonomous Vehicle ("Argo AV") was impacted by a cyclist while traveling east on [XXX] and approaching [XXX]. The Argo AV was traveling in its lane adjacent to a cyclist who was traveling in a marked bike lane. As the Argo AV was passing the cyclist (while maintaining more than 2 meters of lateral margin), the cyclist veered left into the Argo AV's lane. In response, the Argo AV steered away from the cyclist, but the cyclist continued into the lane and the bicycle's left handlebar made contact with the Argo AV's passenger side door handle. The Test Specialist brought the AV to a stop. The cyclist maintained balance, continued to cross the lanes behind the stopped Argo AV, and left the scene after a brief conversation with the left seat Test Specialist, during which the cyclist indicated that he was fine and apologized. The Argo AV sustained minor damage to its passenger side door handle.
"Other" data availability: test vehicle data

We question whether this interaction meets the reporting requirements nevertheless, we are submitting this report out of an abundance of caution. This 10-Day update provides complete information for this incident.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomy had made a right turn from [XXX]. onto [XXX]. in Menlo Park, CA and was preparing to make an immediate, unprotected left turn onto [XXX]. The Zoox vehicle was slowing and moving at approximately 2 mph with its brake lamps and left turn indicator illuminated, yielding to an oncoming vehicle with the right of way. A following vehicle - traveling at approximately 24 mph - then struck the Zoox vehicle's right rear bumper, and that vehicle's driver airbag appeared to have deployed on impact. The Zoox operator disengaged autonomy, proceeded with the left turn, and pulled over. The following vehicle continued its path of travel, veered out of the lane, and collided with a tree on the left side of the road. The Menlo Park Police Department was called to the scene. Two Zoox operators sustained minor injuries and it is unknown if the driver of the other vehicle sustained injuries.

On June [XXX], 2022 at approximately 4:50 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California allegedly contributed to a collision between a passenger vehicle and a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX], according to a claim by the driver of the passenger vehicle.
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode and preparing to enter southbound [XXX] as a passenger vehicle on [XXX] approached from behind.  A pickup truck was traveling next to the passenger vehicle in the adjacent left lane.  As the passenger vehicle approached the Waymo AV from behind, the passenger vehicle entered the adjacent left lane that was occupied by the pickup truck and maneuvered around the Waymo AV.  The pickup truck proceeded without stopping, and the passenger vehicle's driver shortly after signaled to the Waymo AV test driver to pull over.  The Waymo AV test driver then transitioned to manual mode and pulled over.  Transdev has no data or knowledge of any contact between any of the three vehicles.  There was no contact or collision between the Waymo AV and any other vehicle.  However, the driver and passenger in the passenger vehicle have subsequently alleged injuries based on alleged contact between the pick-up truck and passenger vehicle, which contact their allegations attribute to the behavior of Waymo's AV in a bodily injury claim under Waymo's insurance policy.  Waymo received notice of this insurance claim on July [XXX].
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this event under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of 30270-3655-1.

Subject vehicle was on a testing mission in Mountain View, CA.  The vehicle was traveling North-bound on [XXX] operated by the vehicle's Level 4 Automated Driving System and supervised by a safety driver in the driver's designated seating position, and with a safety operator in the front passenger seating position.  Subject vehicle approached a red light to make a right turn East-bound onto [XXX].  The safety operator suggested that the safety driver disengage the ADS and make the turn in manual mode because the vehicle was hesitant in approaching the intersection. The safety driver disengaged the ADS, and, approximately 250ms later, subject vehicle was lightly struck from behind by a white Mazda3.  Having seen debris on the roadway, the driver and operator believed they had run over a rock and did not realize they were hit by the vehicle. After concluding the mission, the driver and operator found damage to a sensor during an inspection.  A subsequent review of video led to discovery of the crash.  No injuries were reported, and law enforcement was not called to the scene.  
In addition to telematics and video, we also have photographs of the vehicle's damaged sensor.

CONTEXT AND HISTORY FOR THIS "OTHER" UPDATED REPORT: Pony.ai originally submitted a monthly report on November [XXX], 2021, and an amended and corrected report on November [XXX], 2021. UNEDITED NARRATIVE FROM ORIGINAL MONTHLY REPORT (11/[XXX]/21) AND AMENDED REPORT (11/[XXX]/21): On October [XXX], 2021, after turning right onto [XXX] from [XXX], the Pony.ai Autonomous Vehicle ("Pony.ai AV") performed a left lane change maneuver in autonomous mode (SAE L4). While performing the lane change, the Pony.ai AV came into contact with a center divider on [XXX]. and the traffic sign that was posted on the divider. The Pony.ai AV suffered moderate damage to the front of the vehicle and the undercarriage. There were no injuries and no other vehicles involved. A passenger vehicle approaching from the right of the Waymo AV on eastbound [XXX] made a left turn in front of the Waymo AV to head northbound on [XXX]. The Waymo AV slowed to a near stop and nudged to its right in order to share the narrow road with the oncoming vehicle and then came to a stop at the stop sign as the oncoming vehicle completed its turn. The Waymo AV sustained minor damage to the sensor hardware housing (which was the reason for towing the Waymo AV) and the passenger vehicle left the scene without exchanging information.

Subject vehicle was on a testing mission in Sunnyvale, CA.  The vehicle was traveling South-bound on [XXX], an eight-lane divided road, operated by the vehicles Level 4 Automated Driving System and supervised by a safety driver in the drivers designated seating position, and with a safety operator in the front passenger seating position.  Subject vehicle moved to the right of the lane to turn right onto West-bound [XXX], a two-lane road, and made contact with a curb at approximately 13-miles per hour.  The safety driver was monitoring the behavior of a vehicle passing in the left lane for signs that it might enter subject vehicles path and did not see subject vehicle moving toward the curb in time to intervene and avoid contact.  During the incident, the safety driver disengaged the Automated Driving System, and then pulled the vehicle to the side of [XXX] and inspected the vehicle and curb for damage.  After the inspection, the safety driver drove the vehicle back to base with the Automated Driving System disengaged.  Subject vehicle did not sustain tire or wheel damage, but the contact resulted in misalignment.  No other agents were involved, no injuries were reported, and law enforcement was not called to the scene. Post-Crash Information: In addition to telematics and video, we also have photographs of the tires, curb, and alignment calibration information.
